        <h2>What is Server Time?</h2>
        <p>
            Server time refers to the internal system clock of the server hosting a website.
            The time displayed on our computers or smartphones is called 'local time', which can vary slightly from
            device to device.
            However, services like ticketing or course registration process requests based solely on <strong>server
                time</strong>.
        </p>

        <div class="blog-highlight">
            <h3>💡 Why is local time different?</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Device time sync cycles:</strong> Windows and macOS sync with time servers only once a week
                    by default.</li>
                <li><strong>Network Latency:</strong> Delays when communicating with time servers create errors.</li>
                <li><strong>OS time handling differences:</strong> Each operating system uses different time-handling
                    algorithms.</li>
                <li><strong>CMOS battery discharge:</strong> When the motherboard's CMOS battery dies, time can reset or
                    drift.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Why 0.1 Seconds Matter</h2>
        <p>
            Ticketing for popular concerts or university course registration involves thousands of people connecting
            simultaneously.
            The server processes requests on a first-come, first-served basis based on packet timestamps.
            If your clock is even 1 second late, your request arrives after others have already been processed.
        </p>

        <div class="info-box"
            style="background-color: #fff4e6; padding: 1rem; border-left: 4px solid #ff9800; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <h3 style="margin-top: 0;">📊 Real Data</h3>
            <p>
                Analysis of a popular idol concert ticketing in 2022:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Within <strong>0.2 seconds</strong> of opening: 95% of tickets gone</li>
                <li>Within <strong>1 second</strong> of opening: 99% of tickets gone</li>
                <li>Average competition ratio: <strong>~1:247</strong> (247 people competing for 1 ticket)</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                In other words, a 0.1-second difference deciding success or failure is not an exaggeration!
            </p>
        </div>

        <h2>Cases of Server vs Local Time Differences</h2>

        <h3>Case 1: Computer Clock is Fast</h3>
        <p>
            If your computer shows 14:00:00 but the actual server time is 13:59:57?
            <strong>Your request is rejected as too early</strong>.
        </p>

        <h3>Case 2: Computer Clock is Slow</h3>
        <p>
            If your computer shows 13:59:58 but the actual server time is 14:00:02?
            You've <strong>arrived 2 seconds late</strong>, waiting behind thousands of people.
        </p>

        <h2>How SyncTime Works</h2>
        <p>
            SyncTime sends an <code>HTTP HEAD</code> request to the target server and analyzes the <code>Date</code>
            information in the response header.
            Going further, it calculates the Round Trip Time (RTT) to mathematically compensate for errors caused by
            network latency.
        </p>

        <div class="code-example" style="background-color: #f5f5f5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 4px; margin: 1rem 0;">
            <h4>Measurement Algorithm</h4>
            <pre style="overflow-x: auto;">
1. Record request start time (t1)
2. Send HTTP HEAD request to server
3. Receive server response
4. Record response reception time (t2)
5. Calculate RTT: t2 - t1
6. Adjust server time: Server Date + (RTT / 2)
            </pre>
        </div>

        <p>
            This allows users to estimate the server's time down to the millisecond, right from their web browser.
            Typically provides accuracy within ±50ms, and up to ±20ms in wired internet environments.
        </p>

        <h2>Practical Success Tips</h2>

        <h3>1. Refresh Timing</h3>
        <p>
            Refresh the page <strong>1-2 seconds before</strong> the server time hits the target.
            You must account for page loading time.
            For example, for a 14:00 opening:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>13:59:58</strong> - Start refresh (recommended)</li>
            <li><strong>13:59:59</strong> - Late but still possible</li>
            <li><strong>14:00:00</strong> - Too late (thousands already ahead)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. NTP Sync</h3>
        <p>
            Synchronizing your computer's clock with standard time (NTP) can reduce basic errors.
            For Windows:
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>Settings → Time & Language → Date & Time</li>
            <li>Turn on "Set time automatically"</li>
            <li>Click "Sync now"</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>3. Use Wired Connection</h3>
        <p>
            A <strong>wired LAN connection</strong> is much more stable and has lower latency than wireless Wi-Fi.
            Wi-Fi is affected by interference, distance, walls, making RTT unstable.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Browser Optimization</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Close all unnecessary tabs</li>
            <li>Clear browser cache (Ctrl + Shift + Delete)</li>
            <li>Disable extensions (ad blockers, etc.)</li>
            <li>Use Chrome (fastest rendering)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>5. Practice</h3>
        <p>
            Before important ticketing, always practice with <strong>mock registration</strong> or <strong>less
                important tickets</strong>.
            Building muscle memory reduces mistakes in real situations.
        </p>

        <h2>SyncTime Strategy</h2>
        <p>
            5 minutes before ticketing, check the target server's time with SyncTime,
            and note the difference from your computer clock.
            For example, if you know "my clock is 1.2 seconds fast,"
            you can adjust your refresh timing accordingly.
        </p>

